# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bitter-pit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bitter-pit/apple] An **apple** is the round, edible fruit of an apple tree (*Malus* spp.).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Fruit trees of the **orchard** or **domestic apple** (***Malus domestica***), the most widely grown in the genus, are cultivated worldwide.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The tree originated in Central Asia, where its wild ancestor, *Malus sieversii*, is still found.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples have been grown for thousands of years in Eurasia before they were introduced to North America by European colonists.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples have cultural significance in many mythologies (including Norse and Greek) and religions (such as Christianity in Europe).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples grown from seeds tend to be very different from those of their parents, and the resultant fruit frequently lacks desired characteristics.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] For commercial purposes, including botanical evaluation, apple cultivars are propagated by clonal grafting onto rootstocks.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple trees grown without rootstocks tend to be larger and much slower to fruit after planting.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Rootstocks are used to control the speed of growth and the size of the resulting tree, allowing for easier harvesting.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] There are more than 7,500 cultivars of apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Different cultivars are bred for various tastes and uses, including cooking, eating raw, and cider or apple juice production.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Trees and fruit are prone to fungal, bacterial, and pest problems, which can be controlled by a number of organic and non-organic means.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In 2010, the fruit's genome was sequenced as part of research on disease control and selective breeding in apple production.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The word *apple* is derived from Old English *æppel*, meaning "fruit", not specifically the apple.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] That in turn is descended from the Proto-Germanic noun **aplaz*, descended in turn from Proto-Indo-European **h₂ébōl*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The apple tree is deciduous, generally standing from 2 to 4.5 metres (6 to 15 feet) tall in cultivation and up to 15 m (49 ft) in the wild, though more typically 2 to 10 m (6.5 to 33 ft).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When cultivated, the size, shape and branch density are determined by rootstock selection and trimming method.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple trees may naturally have a rounded to erect crown with a dense canopy of leaves.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The bark of the trunk is dark gray or gray-brown, but young branches are reddish or dark-brown with a smooth texture.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Young twigs are covered in fine downy hairs; they become hairless when older.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The buds are egg-shaped and dark red or purple in color; they range in size from 3 to 5mm, but are usually less than 4mm.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When emerging from the buds, the leaves are *convolute*, meaning that their edges overlap each other.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Leaves can be simple ovals (elliptic), medium or wide in width, somewhat egg-shaped with the wider portion toward their base (ovate), or even with sides that are more parallel to each other instead of curved (oblong) with a narrow pointed end.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The edges have broadly-angled teeth, but do not have lobes.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The top surface of the leaves are *glabrescent*, almost hairless, while the undersides are densely covered in fine hairs.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The leaves are attached alternately by short leaf stems 1-to-3.5 cm (1⁄2-to-1+1⁄2 in) long.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Blossoms are produced in spring simultaneously with the budding of the leaves and are produced on spurs and some long shoots.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When the flower buds first begin to open the petals are rose-pink and fade to white or light pink when fully open with each flower 3-to-4-centimeter (1-to-1+1⁄2-inch) in diameter.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The five-petaled flowers are group in an inflorescence consisting of a cyme with 3–7 flowers.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The central flower of the inflorescence is called the "king bloom"; it opens first and can develop a larger fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Open apple blossoms are damaged by even brief exposures to temperatures −2 °C (28 °F) or less, although the overwintering wood and buds are hardy down to −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The fruit is a pome that matures in late summer or autumn.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The true fruits or carpels are the harder interior chambers inside the apple's core.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] There are usually five carpels inside an apple, but there may be as few as three.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Each of the chambers contains one or two seeds.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The edible flesh is formed from the receptacle at the base of the flower.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The seeds are egg- to pear-shaped and may be colored from light brown or tan to a very dark brown, often with red shades or even purplish-black.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The five sepals remain attached and stand out from the surface of the apple.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The size of the fruit varies widely between cultivars, but generally has a diameter between 2.5 and 12 cm (1 and 5 in).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The shape is quite variable and may be nearly round, elongated, conical, or short and wide.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The groundcolor of ripe apples is yellow, green, yellow-green or whitish yellow.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The overcolor of ripe apples can be orange-red, pink-red, red, purple-red or brown-red.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The skin may be wholly or partly russeted, making it rough and brown.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The skin is covered in a protective layer of epicuticular wax.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The skin may also be marked with scattered dots.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The flesh is generally pale yellowish-white, though it can be pink, yellow or green.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples can have any amount of overcolor, a darker tint over a pale groundcolor.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The apple as a species has more than 100 alternative scientific names, or synonyms.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In modern times, *Malus pumila* and *Malus domestica* are the two main names in use.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] *M. pumila* is the older name, but *M. domestica* has become much more commonly used starting in the 21st century, especially in the western world.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Two proposals were made to make *M. domestica* a conserved name: the earlier proposal was voted down by the Committee for Vascular Plants of the IAPT in 2014, but in April 2017 the Committee decided, with a narrow majority, that the newly popular name should be conserved.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The General Committee of the IAPT decided in June 2017 to approve this change, officially conserving *M. domestica*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Nevertheless, some works published after 2017 still use *M. pumila* as the correct name, under an alternate taxonomy.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When first classified by Linnaeus in 1753, the pears, apples, and quinces were combined into one genus that he named *Pyrus* and he named the apple as *Pyrus malus*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] However, the botanist Philip Miller published an alternate classification in *The Gardeners Dictionary*, with the apple species separated from *Pyrus*, in 1754.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] He did not clearly indicate that by *Malus pumila* he meant the domesticated apple; nonetheless, the term was used as such by many botanists.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When Moritz Balthasar Borkhausen published his scientific description of the apple in 1803 it may have been a new combination of *P. malus* var.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] *domestica*, but this was not directly referenced by Borkhausen.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] *domestica* for the apple was by Georg Adolf Suckow in 1786.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are diploid, with two sets of chromosomes per cell (though triploid cultivars, with three sets, are not uncommon), have 17 chromosomes and an estimated genome size of approximately 650 Mb.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Several whole genome sequences have been completed and made available.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The first one in 2010 was based on the diploid cultivar 'Golden Delicious'.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] However, this first whole genome sequence contained several errors, in part owing to the high degree of heterozygosity in diploid apples which, in combination with an ancient genome duplication, complicated the assembly.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Recently, double- and trihaploid individuals have been sequenced, yielding whole genome sequences of higher quality.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The first whole genome assembly was estimated to contain around 57,000 genes, though the more recent genome sequences support estimates between 42,000 and 44,700 protein-coding genes.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The availability of whole genome sequences has provided evidence that the wild ancestor of the cultivated apple most likely is *Malus sieversii*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Re-sequencing of multiple accessions has supported this, while also suggesting extensive introgression from *Malus sylvestris* following domestication.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Central Asia is generally considered the center of origin for apples due to the genetic variability in specimens there.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The wild ancestor of *Malus domestica* was *Malus sieversii*, found growing wild in the mountains of Central Asia in southern Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and northwestern China.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Cultivation of the species, most likely beginning on the forested flanks of the Tian Shan mountains, progressed over a long period of time and permitted secondary introgression of genes from other species into the open-pollinated seeds.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Significant exchange with *Malus sylvestris*, the crabapple, resulted in populations of apples being more related to crabapples than to the more morphologically similar progenitor *Malus sieversii*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In strains without recent admixture the contribution of the latter predominates.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Only the *M. sieversii* trees growing on the western side of the Tian Shan mountains contributed genetically to the domesticated apple, not the isolated population on the eastern side.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Chinese soft apples, such as *M. asiatica* and *M. prunifolia*, have been cultivated as dessert apples for more than 2,000 years in China.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] These are thought to be hybrids between *M. baccata* and *M. sieversii* in Kazakhstan.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Among the traits selected for by human growers are size, fruit acidity, color, firmness, and soluble sugar.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Unusually for domesticated fruits, the wild *M. sieversii* origin is only slightly smaller than the modern domesticated apple.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] At the Sammardenchia-Cueis site near Udine in Northeastern Italy, seeds from some form of apples have been found in material carbon dated to between 6570 and 5684 BCE.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Genetic analysis has not yet been successfully used to determine whether such ancient apples were wild *Malus sylvestris* or *Malus domesticus* containing *Malus sieversii* ancestry.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] It is hard to distinguish in the archeological record between foraged wild apples and apple plantations.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] There is indirect evidence of apple cultivation in the third millennium BCE in the Middle East.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] There is direct evidence, apple cores, dated to the 10th century BCE from a Judean site between the Sinai and Negev.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] There was substantial apple production in European classical antiquity, and grafting was certainly known then.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Grafting is an essential part of modern domesticated apple production, to be able to propagate the best cultivars; it is unclear when apple tree grafting was invented.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The Roman writer Pliny the Elder describes a method of storage for apples from his time in the 1st century.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] He says they should be placed in a room with good air circulation from a north facing window on a bed of straw, chaff, or mats with windfalls kept separately.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] These methods extend the shelf life of fresh apples, but refrigeration is still required.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Even sturdy winter varieties only keep well until December in cool climates.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] For longer storage medieval Europeans strung up cored and peeled apples to dry, either whole or sliced into rings.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Of the many Old World plants that the Spanish introduced to Chiloé Archipelago in the 16th century, apple trees became particularly well adapted.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples were introduced to North America by colonists in the 17th century, and the first named apple cultivar was introduced in Boston by Reverend William Blaxton in 1640.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The only apples native to North America are crab apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple cultivars brought as seed from Europe were spread along Native American trade routes, as well as being cultivated on colonial farms.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] An 1845 United States apples nursery catalogue sold 350 of the "best" cultivars, showing the proliferation of new North American cultivars by the early 19th century.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In the 20th century, irrigation projects in Eastern Washington began and allowed the development of the multibillion-dollar fruit industry, of which the apple is the leading product.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Until the 20th century, farmers stored apples in frostproof cellars during the winter for their own use or for sale.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Improved transportation of fresh apples by train and road replaced the necessity for storage.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Controlled atmosphere facilities are used to keep apples fresh year-round.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Controlled atmosphere facilities use high humidity, low oxygen, and controlled carbon dioxide levels to maintain fruit freshness.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] They were first researched at Cambridge University in the 1920s and first used in the United States in the 1950s.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] However, apples must be propagated asexually to obtain cuttings with the characteristics of the parent.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] This is because seedling apples do not "breed true", instead they are "extreme heterozygotes", i.e. rather than resembling their parents, seedlings are all different from each other and from their parents.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Triploid cultivars have an additional reproductive barrier in that three sets of chromosomes cannot be divided evenly during meiosis, yielding unequal segregation of the chromosomes (aneuploids).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Even in the case when a triploid plant can produce a seed (apples are an example), it occurs infrequently, and seedlings rarely survive.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Because apples are not true breeders when planted as seeds, propagation usually involves grafting of cuttings.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The rootstock used for the bottom of the graft can be selected to produce trees of a large variety of sizes, as well as changing the winter hardiness, insect and disease resistance, and soil preference of the resulting tree.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Dwarf rootstocks can be used to produce very small trees (less than 3.0 m or 10 ft high at maturity), which bear fruit many years earlier in their life cycle than full size trees, and are easier to harvest.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Dwarf rootstocks for apple trees can be traced as far back as 300 BCE, to the area of Persia and Asia Minor.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Alexander the Great sent samples of dwarf apple trees to Aristotle's Lyceum.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Dwarf rootstocks became common by the 15th century and later went through several cycles of popularity and decline throughout the world.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The majority of the rootstocks used to control size in apples were developed in England in the early 1900s.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The East Malling Research Station conducted extensive research into rootstocks, and their rootstocks are given an "M" prefix to designate their origin.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Rootstocks marked with an "MM" prefix are Malling-series cultivars later crossed with trees of 'Northern Spy' in Merton, England.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Most new apple cultivars originate as seedlings, which either arise by chance or are bred by deliberately crossing cultivars with promising characteristics.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The words "seedling", "pippin", and "kernel" in the name of an apple cultivar suggest that it originated as a seedling.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples can also form bud sports (mutations on a single branch).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Some bud sports turn out to be improved strains of the parent cultivar.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Some differ sufficiently from the parent tree to be considered new cultivars.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples have been acclimatized in Ecuador at very high altitudes, where they can often, with the needed factors, provide crops twice per year because of constant temperate conditions year-round.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are self-incompatible; they must cross-pollinate to develop fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] During the flowering each season, apple growers often utilize pollinators to carry pollen.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Orchard mason bees are also used as supplemental pollinators in commercial orchards.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Bumblebee queens are sometimes present in orchards, but not usually in sufficient number to be significant pollinators.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Cultivars are sometimes classified by the day of peak bloom in the average 30-day blossom period, with pollinizers selected from cultivars within a 6-day overlap period.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] One cultivar can be pollinated by a compatible cultivar from the same group or close (A with A, or A with B, but not A with C or D).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Cultivars vary in their yield and the ultimate size of the tree, even when grown on the same rootstock.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Some cultivars, if left unpruned, grow very large—letting them bear more fruit, but making harvesting more difficult.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Depending on tree density (number of trees planted per unit surface area), mature trees typically bear 40–200 kg (90–440 lb) of apples each year, though productivity can be close to zero in poor years.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are harvested using three-point ladders that are designed to fit amongst the branches.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Trees grafted on dwarfing rootstocks bear about 10–80 kg (20–180 lb) of fruit per year.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Some farms with apple orchards open them to the public so consumers can pick their own apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Crops ripen at different times of the year according to the cultivar.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Cultivars that yield their crop in the summer include 'Sweet Bough' and 'Duchess'; fall producers include 'Blenheim'; winter producers include 'King', 'Swayzie', and 'Tolman Sweet'.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Commercially, apples can be stored for months in controlled atmosphere chambers.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are commonly stored in chambers with lowered concentrations of oxygen to reduce respiration and slow softening and other changes if the fruit is already fully ripe.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The gas ethylene is used by plants as a hormone which promotes ripening, decreasing the time an apple can be stored.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] For storage longer than about six months the apples are picked earlier, before full ripeness, when ethylene production by the fruit is low.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] However, in many varieties this increases their sensitivity to carbon dioxide, which also must be controlled.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] For home storage, most cultivars of apple can be stored for three weeks in a pantry and four to six weeks from the date of purchase in a refrigerator that maintains 4 to 0 °C (39 to 32 °F).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] 'Granny Smith' and 'Fuji') have more than three times the storage life of others.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Non-organic apples may be sprayed with a substance 1-methylcyclopropene blocking the apples' ethylene receptors, temporarily preventing them from ripening.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Among the most serious disease problems is a bacterial disease called fireblight, and three fungal diseases: *Gymnosporangium* rust, black spot, and bitter rot.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Codling moths, and the apple maggots of fruit flies, cause serious damage to apple fruits, making them unsaleable.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Young apple trees are also prone to mammal pests like mice and deer, which feed on the soft bark of the trees, especially in winter.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The larvae of the apple clearwing moth (red-belted clearwing) burrow through the bark and into the phloem of apple trees, potentially causing significant damage.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] There are more than 7,500 known cultivars (cultivated varieties) of apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Different cultivars are available for temperate and subtropical climates.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The UK's National Fruit Collection in Kent includes over 2,000 apple cultivars.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The University of Reading, responsible for developing the UK national collection database, provides access to search the national collection.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Its work is part of the European Cooperative Programme for Plant Genetic Resources, with 38 countries participating in the Malus/Pyrus work group.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The UK's national fruit collection database contains much information on the characteristics and origin of many apples, including alternative names for what is essentially the same "genetic" apple cultivar.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Most of these cultivars are bred for eating fresh (dessert apples), though some are cultivated specifically for cooking (cooking apples) or producing cider.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Cider apples are typically too tart and astringent to eat fresh, but they give the beverage a rich flavor that dessert apples cannot.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In Europe, apple breeding programs are conducted at places such as Julius Kühn-Institut, the German federal research center for cultivated plants.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In the United States there are many apple breeding programs associated with universities.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] For instance, in the East, Cornell University has had a program operating since 1880 in Geneva, New York, while in the West, Washington State University started a program to support their home state's apple industry in 1994.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Released by the University of Minnesota in 1991, the 'Honeycrisp' has become famous for its crispness and juiciness, thereby commanding high market prices.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Unusually for a popular cultivar, the 'Honeycrisp' is not directly related to another popular apple cultivar but instead to two unsuccessful cultivars.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] However, it is also difficult to grow and to store, prompting the industry to seek hybrids that not only appeal to consumers but are also less costly for farmers to cultivate and last longer in storage.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] By the 2020s, about half of the new apple varieties entering the market in the United States and Canada are 'Honeycrisp' progeny.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Such hybrids include the 'SweeTango' (a cross between the 'Honeycrisp' and the 'Zestar') introduced by the University of Minnesota in 2008 and the 'Cosmic Crisp' (the 'Honeycrisp' and the 'Enterprise') released by Washington State University in 2017.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Commercially popular apple cultivars are soft but crisp.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Other desirable qualities in modern commercial apple breeding are a colorful skin, absence of russeting, ease of shipping, lengthy storage ability, high yields, disease resistance, common apple shape, and developed flavor.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Modern apples are generally sweeter than older cultivars, as popular tastes in apples have varied over time.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Most North Americans and Europeans favor crunchy, sweet, and subacid apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Nevertheless, tart apples maintain a strong minority following.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In the United States today, the most popular apple varieties are the 'Ambrosia', 'Honeycrisp', and 'Jazz', according Nielsen data, while in Canada, the 'Honeycrisp', 'Ambrosia', and 'Gala' take the top spots.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Together, these newer varieties have overtaken once dominant cultivars like the 'McIntosh' and the 'Red Delicious' in the North American market.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Extremely sweet apples with barely any acid flavor are popular in Asia, especially the Indian subcontinent.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Old cultivars are often oddly shaped, russeted, and grow in a variety of textures and colors.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Some find them to have better flavor than modern cultivars, but they may have other problems that make them commercially unviable—low yield, disease susceptibility, poor tolerance for storage or transport, or just being the "wrong" size.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] A few old cultivars are still produced on a large scale, but many have been preserved by home gardeners and farmers who sell directly to local markets.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Many unusual and locally important cultivars with their own unique taste and appearance exist; apple conservation campaigns have sprung up around the world to preserve such local cultivars from extinction.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In the United Kingdom, old cultivars such as 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Egremont Russet' are still commercially important even though by modern standards they are low yielding and susceptible to disease.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] World production of apples in 2023 was 97 million tonnes, with China producing 51% of the total (table).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Secondary producers were the United States, Turkey, and Poland.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple seeds contain small amounts of amygdalin, a sugar and cyanide compound known as a cyanogenic glycoside.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Ingesting small amounts of apple seeds causes no ill effects, but consumption of extremely large doses can cause adverse reactions.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] It may take several hours before the poison takes effect, as cyanogenic glycosides must be hydrolyzed before the cyanide ion is released.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] National Library of Medicine's Hazardous Substances Data Bank records no cases of amygdalin poisoning from consuming apple seeds.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] One form of apple allergy, often found in northern Europe, is called birch-apple syndrome and is found in people who are also allergic to birch pollen.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Allergic reactions are triggered by a protein in apples that is similar to birch pollen, and people affected by this protein can also develop allergies to other fruits, nuts, and vegetables.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Reactions, which entail oral allergy syndrome (OAS), generally involve itching and inflammation of the mouth and throat, but in rare cases can also include life-threatening anaphylaxis.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] This reaction only occurs when raw fruit is consumed—the allergen is neutralized in the cooking process.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The variety of apple, maturity and storage conditions can change the amount of allergen present in individual fruits.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Long storage times can increase the amount of proteins that cause birch-apple syndrome.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In other areas, such as the Mediterranean, some individuals have adverse reactions to apples because of their similarity to peaches.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] This form of apple allergy also includes OAS, but often has more severe symptoms, such as vomiting, abdominal pain and urticaria, and can be life-threatening.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Individuals with this form of allergy can also develop reactions to other fruits and nuts.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Cooking does not break down the protein causing this particular reaction, so affected individuals cannot eat raw or cooked apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Freshly harvested, over-ripe fruits tend to have the highest levels of the protein that causes this reaction.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Breeding efforts have yet to produce a hypoallergenic fruit suitable for either of the two forms of apple allergy.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] A raw apple is 86% water and 14% carbohydrates, with negligible content of fat and protein (table).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] A reference serving of a raw apple with skin weighing 100 g (3.5 oz) provides 52 calories and a moderate content of dietary fiber (table).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Otherwise, there is low content of micronutrients, which are all below 10% of the Daily Value (table).
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple varieties can be grouped as cooking apples, eating apples, and cider apples, the last so astringent as to be "almost inedible".
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are consumed as juice, raw in salads, baked in pies, cooked into sauces and apple butter, or baked.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] They are sometimes used as an ingredient in savory foods, such as sausage and stuffing.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Several techniques are used to preserve apples and apple products.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Traditional methods include drying and making apple butter.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Juice and cider are produced commercially; cider is a significant industry in regions such as the West of England and Normandy.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] A toffee apple (UK) or caramel apple (US) is a confection made by coating an apple in hot toffee or caramel candy respectively and allowing it to cool.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples and honey are a ritual food pairing eaten during the Jewish New Year of Rosh Hashanah.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are an important ingredient in many desserts, such as pies, crumbles, and cakes.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When cooked, some apple cultivars easily form a puree known as apple sauce, which can be cooked down to form a preserve, apple butter.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] They are often baked or stewed, and are cooked in some meat dishes.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples are milled or pressed to produce apple juice, which may be drunk unfiltered (called apple cider in North America), or filtered.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Filtered juice is often concentrated and frozen, then reconstituted later and consumed.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple juice can be fermented to make cider (called hard cider in North America), ciderkin, and vinegar.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Through distillation, various alcoholic beverages can be produced, such as applejack, Calvados, and apple brandy.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Organic apples are commonly produced in the United States.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Due to infestations by key insects and diseases, organic production is difficult in Europe.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The use of pesticides containing chemicals, such as sulfur, copper, microorganisms, viruses, clay powders, or plant extracts (pyrethrum, neem) has been approved by the EU Organic Standing Committee to improve organic yield and quality.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] A light coating of kaolin, which forms a physical barrier to some pests, also may help prevent apple sun scalding.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple skins and seeds contain polyphenols.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] These are oxidised by the enzyme polyphenol oxidase, which causes browning in sliced or bruised apples, by catalyzing the oxidation of phenolic compounds to o-quinones, a browning factor.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Browning reduces apple taste, color, and food value.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Arctic apples, a non-browning group of apples introduced to the United States market in 2019, have been genetically modified to silence the expression of polyphenol oxidase, thereby delaying a browning effect and improving apple eating quality.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The US Food and Drug Administration in 2015, and Canadian Food Inspection Agency in 2017, determined that Arctic apples are as safe and nutritious as conventional apples.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apple seed oil is obtained by pressing apple seeds for manufacturing cosmetics.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In Norse mythology, the goddess Iðunn is portrayed in the *Prose Edda* (written in the 13th century by Snorri Sturluson) as providing apples to the gods that give them eternal youthfulness.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Ellis Davidson links apples to religious practices in Germanic paganism, from which Norse paganism developed.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] She points out that buckets of apples were found in the Oseberg ship burial site in Norway, and that fruits and nuts have been found in the early graves of the Germanic peoples in England and elsewhere in Europe.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The fruits and nuts may have had a symbolic meaning, and nuts are still a recognized symbol of fertility in southwest England.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Rerir's wife's consumption of the apple results in a six-year pregnancy and the birth (by Caesarean section) of their son—the hero Völsung.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Further, Davidson points out the "strange" phrase "Apples of Hel" used in an 11th-century poem by the skald Thorbiorn Brúnarson.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] She states this may imply that the apple was thought of by Brúnarson as the food of the dead.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Further, Davidson notes that the potentially Germanic goddess Nehalennia is sometimes depicted with apples and that parallels exist in early Irish stories.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Davidson asserts that while cultivation of the apple in Northern Europe extends back to at least the time of the Roman Empire and came to Europe from the Near East, the native varieties of apple trees growing in Northern Europe are small and bitter.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Apples appear in many religious traditions, including Greek and Roman mythology where it has an ambiguous symbolism of discord, fertility, or courtship.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In Greek mythology, the Greek hero Heracles, as a part of his Twelve Labours, was required to travel to the Garden of the Hesperides and pick the golden apples off the Tree of Life growing at its center.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The Greek goddess of discord, Eris, became disgruntled after she was excluded from the wedding of Peleus and Thetis.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In retaliation, she tossed a golden apple inscribed Καλλίστη (*Kallistē*, "For the most beautiful one"), into the wedding party.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Three goddesses claimed the apple: Hera, Athena, and Aphrodite.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Paris of Troy was appointed to select the recipient.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] After being bribed by both Hera and Athena, Aphrodite tempted him with the most beautiful woman in the world, Helen of Sparta.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] He awarded the apple to Aphrodite, thus indirectly causing the Trojan War.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The apple was thus considered, in ancient Greece, sacred to Aphrodite.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] To throw an apple at someone was to symbolically declare one's love; and similarly, to catch it was to symbolically show one's acceptance of that love.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Atalanta, also of Greek mythology, raced all her suitors in an attempt to avoid marriage.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] She outran all but Hippomenes (also known as Melanion, a name possibly derived from *melon*, the Greek word for both "apple" and fruit in general), who defeated her by cunning, not speed.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Hippomenes knew that he could not win in a fair race, so he used three golden apples (gifts of Aphrodite, the goddess of love) to distract Atalanta.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] It took all three apples and all of his speed, but Hippomenes was finally successful, winning the race and Atalanta's hand.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In Celtic mythology, the otherworld has many names, including *Emain Ablach*, "Emain of the Apple-trees".
[src:bitter-pit/apple] A version of this is Avalon in Arthurian legend, or in Welsh *Ynys Afallon*, "Island of Apples".
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In China, apples symbolise peace, since the sounds of the first element ("píng") in the words "apple" (苹果, *Píngguǒ*) and "peace" (平安, *Píng'ān*) are homophonous in Mandarin and Cantonese.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] When these two words are combined, the word *Píngānguǒ* (平安果, "Peace apples") is formed.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] This association developed further as the name for Christmas Eve in Mandarin is *Píngānyè* (平安夜, "Peaceful/Quiet Evening"), which made the gifting of apples at this season to friends and associates popular, as a way to wish them peace and safety.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Though the forbidden fruit of Eden in the Book of Genesis is not identified, popular Christian tradition has held that it was an apple that Eve coaxed Adam to share with her.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The origin of the popular identification with a fruit unknown in the Middle East in biblical times is found in wordplay with the Latin words *mālum* (an apple) and *mălum* (an evil), each of which is normally written *malum*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The tree of the forbidden fruit is called "the tree of the knowledge of good and evil" in Genesis 2:17, and the Latin for "good and evil" is *bonum et malum*.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] Renaissance painters may also have been influenced by the story of the golden apples in the Garden of Hesperides.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] As a result, in the story of Adam and Eve, the apple became a symbol for knowledge, immortality, temptation, the fall of man into sin, and sin itself.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The larynx in the human throat has been called the "Adam's apple" because of a notion that it was caused by the forbidden fruit remaining in the throat of Adam.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The apple as symbol of sexual seduction has been used to imply human sexuality, possibly in an ironic vein.
[src:bitter-pit/apple] The proverb, "An apple a day keeps the doctor away", addressing the supposed health benefits of the fruit, has been traced to 19th-century Wales, where the original phrase was "Eat an apple on going to bed, and you'll keep the doctor from earning his bread".
[src:bitter-pit/apple] In the 19th century and early 20th, the phrase evolved to "an apple a day, no doctor to pay" and "an apple a day sends the doctor away"; the phrasing now commonly used was first recorded in 1922.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The disease was probably first reported in Germany where it was known as *Stippen*.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] It was also known as "Baldwin spot" and "blotchy cork" in North America.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The name "bitter pit" was first used by Cobb in Australia in 1895.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The disease has been shown as non-pathological and is now known as a disorder.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] When it occurs on the tree, it is known as "tree pit"; it may also occur in storage, when it is known as "storage pit".
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The affected fruit have dark spots, about ½ cm diameter, which occur on the skin or in the flesh or both.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The cells in the spots are dead (necrotic), and turn brown-black.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Early reports indicated that the disorder was affected by climate and growing conditions.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Dry weather before harvest seemed to increase the condition.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Light crops, heavy use of fertilizers, large fruit and early harvesting increased the condition.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Fruit that were free of bitter pit at harvest were often severely affected after a short period of storage.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Bitter pit has been widely reviewed over many decades.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The disorder became a major problem for exports from the Southern Hemisphere to Europe.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The breakthrough in control came with the discovery in North America that the mineral calcium was low in affected fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Several decades of research in several countries with many cultivars showed that moderate levels of bitter pit could be controlled with the spraying of the trees with calcium chloride or calcium nitrate during the growing season.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] However, in the southern hemisphere where highly susceptible fruit had to be harvested early for export to Europe, the problem remained.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] An attempt to increase the calcium content by applying calcium after harvest had resulted in severe injury to the fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Export of susceptible apples from New Zealand was under threat and new methods for controlling bitter pit were investigated.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] While it was shown that bitter pit was reduced as calcium levels rose, it was not possible to determine a minimum level of calcium that would ensure that the disorder was controlled.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The most effective treatment found for closed calyx fruit was to submerge the fruit in the calcium chloride solution and to apply a vacuum and immediately rinse in water.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] This overcame the injury problem and gave much better control of the disorder.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] The vacuum treatment was commercialized in New Zealand for the Cox's Orange Pippin cultivar in 1978, and was used for several years.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] However the treatment was expensive and could not be used for open calyx cultivars.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] A simpler treatment was developed in Western Australia and was adopted in Australia and in New Zealand.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] This involved dipping the fruit in the calcium solution and rinsing in water after about 36 hours.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] This treatment has been confirmed by independent workers and has generally been adopted in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Postharvest dipping in a calcium solution has been recommended in some other countries where bitter pit is severe.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] However the problem of fruit injury does not seem to have been addressed.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] It appears that bitter pit can generally be reduced by using good horticultural practices.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Usually spraying throughout the growing season with a calcium salt is also necessary for moderately susceptible cultivars.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] It is more difficult to control storage pit in highly susceptible cultivars as field spraying may not be able to apply sufficient calcium to the fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-pit] Improved control can be obtained by also dipping the fruit in a 2–3 per cent calcium chloride solution after harvest and rinsing the fruit in water after about 36 hours.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] The term “bitter rot” has consistently been associated with this disease in literature from the United States going back through the 1800s.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] During the 1950s to 1980s there was literature out of Great Britain and Ireland that used the common name of “bitter rot” for apple rots caused by *Neofabraea* (or the older synonym of *Gloeosporium*) species, which are now referred to as lenticel rot or bulls eye rot.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Literature from South Korea often uses the name of "apple anthracnose".
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Some scientists distinguish between rots caused by the *C. gloeosporioides* and *C. acutatum* species complexes, calling them "Glomerella rot" and "bitter rot", respectively.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] However "bitter rot" or the more specific "bitter rot of apple" or "apple bitter rot" are the most common terms used in English language literature.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] In the United States it was noted that the fungi that cause bitter rot could broadly be divided into an asexual northern form and a faster-growing perithecia-producing (sexually reproducing) southern form.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Though rarely used to describe the fungus that caused bitter rot, the anamorph (asexual form) went by multiple different names that usually differed based on what host plant they were isolated from.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] In 1957 the great lumper of fungal species Josef Adolf von Arx created some order out of the chaos and synonymized over 600 fungal names into the single name of *Colletotrichum gloeosporioides*.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] However, von Arx went just a touch too far, and less than a decade later the isolates that had acute (pointed) conidia (asexual spores) were named *Colletotrichum acutatum*.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] *G. cingulata* and *C. gloeosporioides* were the teleomorph and anamorph (sexual and asexual) stages of the same fungus, while *C. acutatum* was an anamorph for which a teleomorph was almost never observed.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] While the name of *G. cingulata* was most common, the fungi that cause bitter rot were categorized under the names of *G. cingulata, C. gloeosporioides,* and *C. acutatum* up through the early 2000s.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] With the development of species identification based on molecular phylogenetics, determination of the sexual stage was no required and the single genus name of *Colletotrichum* was chosen as the holomorph.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Using molecular phylogenetics the *C. gloeosporioides* and *C. acutatum* species were each split up into several dozen new species, which are now grouped together as species complexes.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Of these *C. fioriniae, C. godetiae,* and *C. nymphaeae* are by far the most common species associated with bitter rot.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Within the *C. gloeosporioides* species complex, *C. fructicola, C. chrysophilum, C. siamense, C. noveboracense, C. tropicale, C. alienum, C. theobromicola* (syn.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] *C. fragariae*), *C. aenigma, C. kahawae, C. gloeosporioides* sensu stricto, and *C. henanense* have been identified as causing bitter rot.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Of these *C. fructicola, C. chrysophilum, C. siamense*, and *C. noveboracense* are by far the most common species associated with bitter rot.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Of the two species complexes, the *C. gloeosporioides* species complex tends to have higher optimal growth temperatures and faster growth than the *C. acutatum* species complex.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] The surface of rots caused by the *C. gloeosporioides* species complex tend to be smooth, while those caused by the *C. acutatum* species complex tend to have concentric rings of acervuli that produce salmon-colored masses of conidia.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Within the two species complexes, the individual species are not known to differ substantially from each other in horticulturally significant ways.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Both species complexes are hemibiotrophs, and the primary ecological niche of many of these species is likely endophytic.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] The *Colletotrichum* species that cause bitter rot overwinter in infected fruit mummies, buds, twigs, and branch cankers.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Under humid conditions infected apples that drop to the soil surface in the fall are not a significant source of inoculum the next year, as *Colletotrichum* will generally be succeeded by various yeasts.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Spores are dispersed throughout the year during periods of leaf wetness when the temperature is between 10°C and 32°C.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Apple fruit can become infected during the growing season anytime spores are available and temperature and wetness hours are optimal for infection.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] In a pattern typical of hemibiotrophs, the bitter rot infection will establish itself without causing rot, then will often wait until the fruit ripens and is less resistant to rot to switch to necrotrophy and form the dark sunken bitter rot lesions.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Fruit that is infected during the summer will often not show any symptoms of rot until close to or after harvest.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Even with good horticultural practices, successful control of bitter rot on susceptible cultivars under warm and wet conditions requires regular applications of fungicides.
[src:bitter-pit/bitter-rot-of-apple] Fungicides should be applied before infection occurs as few if any registered fungicides have good curative activity.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is commonly encountered as a hydrated solid with generic formula CaCl2·*n*H2O, where *n* = 0, 1, 2, 4, and 6.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] These compounds are mainly used for de-icing and dust control.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Because the anhydrous salt is hygroscopic and deliquescent, it is used as a desiccant.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride was apparently discovered in the 15th century but wasn't studied properly until the 18th century.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] By depressing the freezing point of water, calcium chloride is used to prevent ice formation and is used to de-ice.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] This application consumes the greatest amount of calcium chloride.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is relatively harmless to plants and soil.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] As a de-icing agent, it is much more effective at lower temperatures than sodium chloride.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] When distributed for this use, it usually takes the form of small, white spheres a few millimeters in diameter, called prills.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Solutions of calcium chloride can prevent freezing at temperatures as low as −52 °C (−62 °F), making it ideal for filling agricultural implement tires as a liquid ballast, aiding traction in cold climates.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is also used in domestic and industrial chemical air dehumidifiers.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The second largest application of calcium chloride exploits its hygroscopic nature and the tackiness of its hydrates; calcium chloride is highly hygroscopic and its hydration is an exothermic process.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] A concentrated solution keeps a liquid layer on the surface of dirt roads, which suppresses the formation of dust.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The liquid layer keeps the finer dust particles on the road, providing a cushioning layer.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] If these are allowed to blow away, the large aggregate begins to shift around and the road breaks down.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Using calcium chloride reduces the need for grading by as much as 50% and the need for fill-in materials as much as 80%.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] In the food industry, calcium chloride is frequently employed as a firming agent in canned vegetables, particularly for canned tomatoes and cucumber pickles.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] It is also used in firming soybean curds into tofu and in producing a caviar substitute from vegetable or fruit juices.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] It is also used to enhance the texture of various other products, such as whole apples, whole hot peppers, whole and sliced strawberries, diced tomatoes, and whole peaches.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride's freezing-point depression properties are used to slow the freezing of the caramel in caramel-filled chocolate bars.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Also, it is frequently added to sliced apples to maintain texture.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] In brewing beer, calcium chloride is sometimes used to correct mineral deficiencies in the brewing water.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] It affects flavor and chemical reactions during the brewing process, and can also affect yeast function during fermentation.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] In cheesemaking, calcium chloride is sometimes added to processed (pasteurized/homogenized) milk to restore the natural balance between calcium and protein in casein.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is also commonly used as an electrolyte in sports drinks and other beverages; as a food additive used in conjunction with other inorganic salts it adds taste to bottled water.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The average intake of calcium chloride as food additives has been estimated to be 160–345 mg/d.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is permitted as a food additive in the European Union for use as a sequestrant and firming agent with the E number **E509**.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is generally recognized as safe (GRAS) by the U.S.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Its use in organic crop production is generally prohibited under the US National Organic Program.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride has a very salty taste and can cause mouth and throat irritation at high concentrations, so it is typically not the first choice for long-term oral supplementation (as a calcium supplement).
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is highly soluble in water and efficiently absorbed from the intestine.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The dissolution of calcium chloride in water is exothermic; releasing energy as heat.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] If undissolved calcium chloride is ingested, this can lead to burns in the mouth, throat, esophagus, and stomach.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Ingestion of large amounts of undissolved calcium chloride has been reported to result in burns, and rarely, necrosis of the stomach.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The extremely salty taste of calcium chloride is used to flavor pickles without increasing the food's sodium content.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is used to prevent cork spot and bitter pit on apples by spraying on the tree during the late growing season.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Drying tubes are frequently packed with calcium chloride.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Kelp is dried with calcium chloride for use in producing sodium carbonate.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Anhydrous calcium chloride has been approved by the FDA as a packaging aid to ensure dryness (CPG 7117.02).
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The hydrated salt can be dried for re-use but will dissolve in its own water of hydration if heated quickly and form a hard amalgamated solid when cooled.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Similarly, CaCl2 is used as a flux and electrolyte in the FFC Cambridge electrolysis process for titanium production, where it ensures the proper exchange of calcium and oxygen ions between the electrodes.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride infusions may be used as an intravenous therapy to prevent hypocalcemia.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is a highly soluble calcium salt.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride when taken orally completely dissociates into calcium ions (Ca2+) in the gastrointestinal tract, resulting in readily bioavailable calcium.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The high concentration of calcium ions facilitates efficient absorption in the small intestine.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] However, the use of calcium chloride as a source of calcium taken orally is less common compared to other calcium salts because of potential adverse effects such as gastrointestinal irritation and discomfort.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] When tasted, calcium chloride exhibits a distinctive bitter flavor alongside its salty taste.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] While chloride ions (Cl−) primarily contribute to saltiness, at higher concentrations, they can enhance the bitter sensation.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The combination of calcium and chloride ions intensifies the overall bitterness.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] At lower concentrations, calcium chloride may taste predominantly salty.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The salty taste arises from the electrolyte nature of the compound, similar to sodium chloride (table salt).
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] As the concentration increases, the bitter taste becomes more pronounced: the increased presence of calcium ions enhances the activation of bitterness receptors.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is used in concrete mixes to accelerate the initial setting, but chloride ions lead to corrosion of steel rebar, so it should not be used in reinforced concrete.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The anhydrous form of calcium chloride may also be used for this purpose and can provide a measure of the moisture in concrete.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is included as an additive in plastics and in fire extinguishers, in blast furnaces as an additive to control scaffolding (clumping and adhesion of materials that prevent the furnace charge from descending), and in fabric softener as a thinner.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The exothermic dissolution of calcium chloride is used in self-heating cans and heating pads.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is used as a water hardener in the maintenance of hot tub water, as insufficiently hard water can lead to corrosion and foaming.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] In the oil industry, calcium chloride is used to increase the density of solids-free brines.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The salt is also used to provide inhibition of swelling clays in the water phase of invert emulsion drilling fluids.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride (CaCl 2) acts as flux material, decreasing the melting point, in the Davy process for the industrial production of sodium metal through the electrolysis of molten NaCl.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is also used in the production of activated charcoal.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride can be used to precipitate fluoride ions from water as insoluble CaF 2.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride is also an ingredient used in ceramic slipware.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] It suspends clay particles so that they float within the solution, making it easier to use in a variety of slipcasting techniques.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] For watering plants to use as a fertilizer, a moderate concentration of calcium chloride is used to avoid potential toxicity: 5 to 10 mM solutions are generally effective and safe for most plants.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The range is 0.55–1.11 g (0.019–0.039 oz) of anhydrous calcium chloride (CaCl2) per liter of water or 1.10–2.19 g (0.039–0.077 oz) of calcium chloride hexahydrate (CaCl2·6H2O) per liter of water.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride dihydrate (20 percent by weight) dissolved in ethanol (95 percent ABV) has been used as a sterilant for male animals.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The solution is injected into the testes of the animal.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Within one month, necrosis of testicular tissue results in sterilization.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Cocaine producers in Colombia import tons of calcium chloride to recover solvents that are on the INCB Red List and are more tightly controlled.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Although the salt is non-toxic in small quantities when wet, the strongly hygroscopic properties of non-hydrated calcium chloride present some hazards.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The compound can act as an irritant by desiccating moist skin.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Solid calcium chloride dissolves exothermically, and burns can result in the mouth and esophagus if it is ingested.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Ingestion of concentrated solutions or solid products may cause gastrointestinal irritation or ulceration.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Consumption of calcium chloride can lead to hypercalcemia.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride dissolves in water, producing chloride and the aquo complex [Ca(H2O)6]2+.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] In this way, these solutions are sources of "free" calcium and free chloride ions.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride has a very high enthalpy change of solution, indicated by considerable temperature rise accompanying dissolution of the anhydrous salt in water.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] This property is the basis for its largest-scale application.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Aqueous solutions of calcium chloride tend to be slightly acidic due to the influence of the chloride ions on the hydrogen ion concentration in water.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The slight acidity of calcium chloride solutions is primarily due to the increased ionic strength of the solution, which can influence the activity of hydrogen ions and lower the pH slightly.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] In the US, most calcium chloride is obtained by purification from brine.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] As with most bulk commodity salt products, trace amounts of other cations from the alkali metals and alkaline earth metals (groups 1 and 2) and other anions from the halogens (group 17) typically occur.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Calcium chloride occurs as the rare evaporite minerals sinjarite (dihydrate) and antarcticite (hexahydrate).
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] Another natural hydrate known is ghiaraite – a tetrahydrate.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The related minerals chlorocalcite (potassium calcium chloride, KCaCl3) and tachyhydrite (calcium magnesium chloride, CaMg2Cl6·12H2O) are also very rare.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-chloride] The same is true for rorisite, CaClF (calcium chloride fluoride).
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Acidic, sandy, or coarse soils often contain less calcium.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Uneven soil moisture and overuse of fertilizers can also cause calcium deficiency.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] At times, even with sufficient calcium in the soil, it can be in an insoluble form and is then unusable by the plant or it could be attributed to a "transport protein".
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Soils containing high phosphorus are particularly susceptible to creating insoluble forms of calcium.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Calcium and magnesium are opposed within the plant cells, and have antagonistic interactions.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] As a result, a homeostatic balance between Ca and Mg within the plant is necessary for optimal growth and proper development.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Calcium deficiency symptoms appear initially as localized tissue necrosis leading to stunted plant growth, necrotic leaf margins on young leaves or curling of the leaves, and eventual death of terminal buds and root tips.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Generally, the new growth and rapidly growing tissues of the plant are affected first.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] The mature leaves are rarely if ever affected because calcium accumulates to high concentrations in older leaves.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Calcium deficiencies in plants are associated with reduced height, fewer nodes, and less leaf area.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] ' – fruit skins develop pits, brown spots appear on skin and/or in flesh and taste of those areas is bitter.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] , "water cored" apples seldom display bitter pit effects.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] There is some evidence that plants like lettuce are more likely to experience tipburn (burned edges of leaves) if they're experiencing a deficiency of calcium.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] 'Blossom end rot' – Symptoms start as sunken, dry decaying areas at the blossom end of the fruit, furthest away from the stem, not all fruit on a truss is necessarily affected.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Sometimes rapid growth from high-nitrogen fertilizers may exacerbate blossom end rot.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Water management and preventing water stress is key to minimizing its occurrence.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Although it was once common knowledge that blossom end rot was caused by calcium deficiencies, there are also other proposed causes.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Calcium deficiency can sometimes be rectified by adding agricultural lime to acid soils, aiming at a pH of 6.5, unless the subject plants specifically prefer acidic soil.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Organic matter should be added to the soil to improve its moisture-retaining capacity.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] However, because of the nature of the disorder (i.e. poor transport of calcium to low transpiring tissues), the problem cannot generally be cured by the addition of calcium to the roots.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] In some species, the problem can be reduced by prophylactic spraying with calcium chloride of tissues at risk.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Plant damage is difficult to reverse, so corrective action should be taken immediately, supplemental applications of calcium nitrate at 200 ppm nitrogen, for example.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Soil pH should be tested, and corrected if needed, because calcium deficiency is often associated with low pH.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Early fruit will generally have the worst symptoms, with them typically lessening as the season progresses.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-deficiency-plant-disorder] Preventative measures, such as irrigating prior to especially high temperatures and stable irrigation will minimize the occurrence.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Norgessalpeter was synthesized at Notodden, Norway in 1905 by the Birkeland–Eyde process.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Most of the world's calcium nitrate is now made in Porsgrunn.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The fertilizer grade (15.5-0-0 + 19% Ca) is popular in the greenhouse and hydroponics trades; it contains ammonium nitrate and water, as the "double salt" 5Ca(NO3)2·NH4NO3·10H2O.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] This is called calcium ammonium nitrate and often the name calcium nitrate prill is used as it always comes in a prilled (granular) form.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] A liquid formulation (9-0-0 + 11 Ca) is also offered.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] An anhydrous, air-stable derivative is the urea complex Ca(NO3)2·4[OC(NH2)2], which has been sold as Calurea.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Calcium nitrate is also used to control certain plant diseases.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] For example, dilute calcium nitrate (and calcium chloride) sprays are used to control bitter pit and cork spot in apple trees.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Calcium nitrate is used in waste water pre-conditioning for odour emission prevention.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The waste water pre-conditioning is based on establishing an anoxic biology in the waste water system.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] In the presence of nitrate, the metabolism for sulfates stops, thus preventing formation of hydrogen sulfide.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Additionally, easily degradable organic matter is consumed, which otherwise can cause anaerobic conditions downstream as well as odour emissions itself.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The concept is also applicable for surplus sludge treatment.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Calcium nitrate is used in concrete admixtures to accelerate setting.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] This use with concrete and mortar is based on two effects.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The calcium ion accelerates formation of calcium hydroxide and thus precipitation and setting.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] This effect is used also in cold weather concreting agents as well as some combined plasticizers.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The nitrate ion leads to formation of iron hydroxide, whose protective layer reduces corrosion of the concrete reinforcement.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Calcium nitrate is a very common coagulant in latex production, especially in dipping processes.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Dissolved calcium nitrate is a part of the dipping bath solution.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The warm former is dipped into the coagulation liquid and a thin film of the dipping liquid remains on the former.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] When now dipping the former into the latex the calcium nitrate will break up the stabilization of the latex solution and the latex will coagulate on the former.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] The dissolution of calcium nitrate tetrahydrate is highly endothermic (cooling).
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] For this reason, calcium nitrate tetrahydrate is sometimes used for regenerable cold packs.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Calcium nitrate can be used as a part of molten salt mixtures.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Typical are binary mixtures of calcium nitrate and potassium nitrate or ternary mixtures including also sodium nitrate.
[src:bitter-pit/calcium-nitrate] Those molten salts can be used to replace thermo oil in concentrated solar power plants for the heat transfer, but mostly those are used in heat storage.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] A **sepal** (/ˈsɛpəl, ˈsiːpəl/) is a part of the flower of angiosperms (flowering plants).
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Usually green, sepals typically function as protection for the flower in bud, and often as support for the petals when in bloom.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Collectively, the sepals are called the ***calyx*** or ***calix***.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The term *sepalum* was coined by Noël Martin Joseph de Necker in 1790, and derived from Ancient Greek σκέπη*(*sképē*)* 'covering'.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Collectively, the sepals are called the *calyx* (plural: calyces), the outermost whorl of parts that form a flower.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The word *calyx* was adopted from the Latin *calyx*, not to be confused with *calix* 'cup, goblet'.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The Latin *calyx* is derived from Greek κάλυξ *kalyx* 'bud, calyx, husk, wrapping' (cf.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Sanskrit *kalika* 'bud'), while *calix* is derived from Greek κύλιξ *kylix* 'cup, goblet'; both words have been used interchangeably in botanical Latin.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The term *tepal* is usually applied when the parts of the perianth are difficult to distinguish, e.g. the petals and sepals share the same color or the petals are absent and the sepals are colorful.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] When the undifferentiated tepals resemble petals, they are referred to as "petaloid", as in petaloid monocots, orders of monocots with brightly colored tepals.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Since they include Liliales, an alternative name is lilioid monocots.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Examples of plants in which the term tepal is appropriate include genera such as *Aloe* and *Tulipa*.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] In contrast, genera such as *Rosa* and *Phaseolus* have well-distinguished sepals and petals.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The number of sepals in a flower is its merosity.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Flower merosity is indicative of a plant's classification.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The merosity of a eudicot flower is typically four or five.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The merosity of a monocot or palaeodicot flower is three, or a multiple of three.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The development and form of the sepals vary considerably among flowering plants.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] They may be free (polysepalous) or fused together (gamosepalous).
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Often, the sepals are much reduced, appearing somewhat awn-like, or as scales, teeth, or ridges.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Most often such structures protrude until the fruit is mature and falls off.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Examples of flowers with much-reduced perianths are found among the grasses.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] In some flowers, the sepals are fused towards the base, forming a *calyx tube* (as in the families Lythraceae and Fabaceae).
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Rosaceae and Myrtaceae), a hypanthium includes the bases of sepals, petals, and the attachment points of the stamens.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Mechanical cues may be responsible for sepal growth and there is a strong evidence suggesting that microtubules are present and determine the tensile strength and direction of growth at a molecular level.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Morphologically, both sepals and petals are modified leaves.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] The calyx (the sepals) and the corolla (the petals) are the outer sterile whorls of the flower, which together form the *perianth*.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] In some plants, such as *Aristolochia*, the calyx is the primary whorl, forming a flower up to 50 cm (20 in) wide, with one sepal growing to a slender ribbon with a length of up to 4 m (13 ft) in *Aristolochia grandiflora*, the largest of all calyces.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Sepals typically function as protection for the flower in bud, and often as support for the petals when in bloom.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Similarly to ordinary leaves, sepals are capable of performing photosynthesis.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] However, photosynthesis in sepals occurs at a slower rate than in ordinary leaves due to sepals having a lower stomatal density which limits the spaces for gas exchange.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] After flowering, most plants have no more use for the calyx, which withers or becomes vestigial, although in a few plants such as *Lodoicea* and *Solanum melongena* (aubergine, brinjal) the calyx grows along with the fruit, possibly to protect the attachment point.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Some plants retain a thorny calyx, either dried or live, as protection for the fruit or seeds.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] Examples include species of *Acaena*, some of the Solanaceae (for example the tomatillo *Physalis philadelphica*), and the water caltrop, *Trapa natans*.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] In some species, the calyx not only persists after flowering but instead of withering, begins to grow until it forms a bladder-like enclosure around the fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] This is an effective protection against some kinds of birds and insects, for example in *Hibiscus trionum* and in *Physalis* species.
[src:bitter-pit/calyx-flower] In some other plants, the calyx grows into an accessory fruit.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] Though the parentage of the cultivar is unknown, Ribston Pippin seems a likely candidate.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] DNA analysis of major apple pedigrees has suggested Margil as the parent of Cox, with Ribston Pippin being another Margil seedling.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] The variety was introduced for sale by the 1850s by Charles Turner, and grown commercially from the 1860s, particularly in the Vale of Evesham in Worcestershire, and later in Kent.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] 'Cox's Orange Pippin' is highly regarded for its excellent flavour and attractive appearance.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] The apples are of medium size, orange-red in colour, deepening to bright red and mottled with carmine over a deep yellow background.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] The flesh is very aromatic, yellow-white, fine-grained, crisp, and very juicy.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] Cox's flavour is sprightly subacid, with hints of cherry and anise, becoming softer and milder with age.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] When ripe apples are shaken, the seeds make a rattling sound as they are only loosely held in the apple's flesh.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] Cox's Orange Pippin is often blended with other varieties in the production of cider and is also used to produce high-quality apple juice, particularly in artisanal or premium cold-pressed forms.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] According to the Institute of Food Research, Cox's Orange Pippin accounts for over 50% of the UK acreage of dessert apples.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] The tree is a moderate grower and is annually productive.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] However, it can be difficult to grow in many environments, and tends to be susceptible to diseases such as scab, mildew, and canker, so it is rarely grown commercially in North America.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] Cox's Orange Pippin is also grown in Belgium and in the Netherlands, countries with a climate similar to that of Great Britain.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] In addition to the cultivation of Cox sports, apple breeders have hybridised Cox with other varieties to improve vigour, disease resistance, and yield, while attempting to retain the unique qualities of Cox's flavour.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] A number of sports of Cox's Orange Pippin have been discovered over subsequent years and propagated.
[src:bitter-pit/cox-s-orange-pippin] These retain "Cox" in their names, e.g., Cherry Cox, Crimson Cox, King Cox, and Queen Cox.
